data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with specific MSTest 3.x+ assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed:**

| Before (`Assert.IsTrue`) | After (specific assertion) |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` check stays as `Assert.IsTrue` — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" API, and `IsTrue` is appropriate here.

**Why this matters:** Specific assertions produce better failure messages. For example, `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` will report _"Expected 3 items but found 5"_ instead of just _"Assert.IsTrue failed"_.
